{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11997"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11997"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.26,0.04,0.01,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96646"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33141"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96646"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother due to passage of bloody stools and mucus. The mother reports that the child has been experiencing episodes of crying suggestive of abdominal pain. He draws his legs up to relieve the pain somewhat. He has no significant medical history apart from a runny nose and cough two weeks ago. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a long, thin mass palpable in the right upper quadrant without signs of peritonism. Intravenous access is established, appropriate analgesia is given, and the child is kept nil by mouth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen","Air enema","Laparotomy","Colonoscopy","Ultrasound scan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has the classical clinical features of intussusception, namely abdominal pain, blood per rectum, and abdominal mass. Intussusception results from invagination of a proximal segment of bowel into the distal bowel lumen. The most common type seen in children is ileo-colic where invagination starts in the distal ileum close to the ileocolic junction. Ileo-ileal and colo-colic intussusceptions are uncommon in children. With no signs of bowel perforation or obstruction, \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to confirm the diagnosis of intussusception with high sensitivity and specificity, particularly when performed by a paediatric ultrasonographer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAir enema\u003C/strong\u003E can be both diagnostic and therapeutic in patients with ileo-colic intussusception and is typically used following ultrasound confirmation. If peritonitis, perforation, systemic toxicity, and shock are not present, most patients can be successfully managed with this intervention and do not require surgery. Pneumatic reduction (using air) or hydrostatic reduction (using saline) are currently preferred. Immediate management should be instituted to avoid the complication of ischaemic bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E would not be first-line investigation in this young patient due to the risk of radiation exposure as well as the high sensitivity and specificity of ultrasound in diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf signs of peritonitis, perforation, or bowel ischaemia are present, then \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated. Bowel resection may be required if reduction is not possible or there is evidence of ischaemia/necrosis. Recurrence is surprisingly uncommon after either surgical or nonsurgical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not used in the management of intussusception. It may have diagnostic and rarely therapeutic value in adults with colo-colic intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the first-line investigation to confirm the diagnosis of intussusception when signs of bowel obstruction or perforation are absent.","In intussusception with perforation or peritonitis, urgent surgical review is required."],"references":["Gluckman S, Karpelowsky J, Webster AC, McGee RG. Management for intussusception in children. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews 2017, Issue 6. Art. No.: CD006476. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD006476.pub3. Available at: https://www.cochrane.org/CD006476/COLOCA_management-intussusception-children"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11997"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T15:04:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T15:04:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"9